    "reasoning": "1. **State Machine Design**: We need to implement a serial receiver (UART-like). The states required are: \n   - `IDLE`: Waiting for the start bit (transition from 1 to 0).\n   - `START_BIT`: Validating the start bit (though usually, the transition to IDLE to START_BIT implies it, we wait one cycle to ensure it stays 0).\n   - `DATA_BITS`: Collecting 8 bits of data. Since the LSB is sent first, we will shift them into a register.\n   - `STOP_BIT`: Checking the stop bit (must be 1).\n   - `WAIT_FOR_STOP`: If the stop bit was wrong (0), we must wait until the line returns to 1 before looking for a new start bit.\n\n2. **Data Handling**: A shift register or a counter-based approach will collect 8 bits. Since the LSB comes first, `out_byte <= {in, out_byte[7:1]}` or similar logic is needed. A more robust way is `data_reg[bit_count] <= in`.\n\n3. **Done Signal**: The `done` signal must assert when a valid stop bit is found. The specification says 'assert done each time it finds a stop bit'. This implies even if the data was corrupted by a missing stop bit previously, once a stop bit is found, we signal completion.\n\n4. **Error Handling**: If the stop bit is not 1, the FSM enters a state to wait for the line to go high (idle) before returning to IDLE to prevent misinterpreting the trailing 0s as start bits.\n\n5. **Implementation Details**:\n   - Use `localparam` for state encoding.\n   - Use a counter to track the 8 bits.\n   - Use a synchronous reset.\n   - Initialize signals using an `initial` block to avoid X-propagation.\n\n6. **Advice to avoid syntax errors**:\n   - Ensure all signals are declared as `logic`.\n   - Use `always @(*)` for combinational logic.\n   - Use `always @(posedge clk)` for sequential logic.\n   - Avoid `unique` or `inside` as per requirements.\n   - Ensure the `out_byte` is only valid when `done` is 1.",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input  logic       clk,\n    input  logic       in,\n    input  logic       reset,\n    output logic [7:0] out_byte,\n    output logic       done\n);\n\n    // State definitions\n    localparam STATE_IDLE      = 3'd0;\n    localparam STATE_START_BIT = 3'd1;\n    localparam STATE_DATA_BITS = 3'd2;\n    localparam STATE_STOP_BIT  = 3'd3;\n    localparam STATE_ERROR_WAIT= 3'd4;\n\n    logic [2:0] state;\n    logic [2:0] state_next;\n    logic [2:0] bit_cnt;\n    logic [7:0] shift_reg;\n    logic       done_reg;\n    logic [7:0] out_byte_reg;\n\n    // Initialize signals to prevent X\n    initial begin\n        state = STATE_IDLE;\n        bit_cnt = 3'd0;\n        shift_reg = 8'd0;\n        done_reg = 1'b0;\n        out_byte_reg = 8'd0;\n    end\n\n    // Sequential logic\n    always @(posedge clk) begin\n        if (reset) begin\n            state <= STATE_IDLE;\n            bit_cnt <= 3'd0;\n            shift_reg <= 8'd0;\n            done_reg <= 1'b0;\n            out_byte_reg <= 8'd0;\n        end else begin\n            state <= state_next;\n            \n            case (state)\n                STATE_IDLE:\n                    begin\n                        done_reg <= 1'b0;\n                        bit_cnt <= 3'd0;\n                    end\n\n                STATE_START_BIT:\n                    begin\n                        // We already detected the transition to 0 in IDLE\n                        // Just move to data collection\n                        bit_cnt <= 3'd0;\n                    end\n\n                STATE_DATA_BITS:\n                    begin\n                        shift_reg[bit_cnt] <= in;\n                        if (bit_cnt == 3'd7) begin\n                            bit_cnt <= 3'd0;\n                        end else begin\n                            bit_cnt <= bit_cnt + 3'd1;\n                        end\n                    end\n\n                STATE_STOP_BIT:\n                    begin\n                        if (in == 1'b1) begin\n                            // Valid stop bit\n                            done_reg <= 1'b1;\n                            out_byte_reg <= shift_reg;\n                        end else begin\n                            // Invalid stop bit\n                            done_reg <= 1'b0;\n                        end\n                    end\n\n                STATE_ERROR_WAIT:\n                    begin\n                        if (in == 1'b1) begin\n                            done_reg <= 1'b0;\n                        end else begin\n                            done_reg <= 1'b0;\n                        end\n                    end\n                \n                default:\n                    begin\n                        done_reg <= 1'b0;\n                    end\n            endcase\n        end\n    end\n\n    // Next state combinational logic\n    always @(*) begin\n        state_next = state;\n        case (state)\n            STATE_IDLE:\n                begin\n                    if (in == 1'b0) state_next = STATE_START_BIT;\n                    else state_next = STATE_IDLE;\n                end\n\n            STATE_START_BIT:\n                begin\n                    // The spec says identify start bit (0), then wait for 8 bits.\n                    // We assume the bit detected in IDLE was the start bit.\n                    state_next = STATE_DATA_BITS;\n                end\n\n            STATE_DATA_BITS:\n                begin\n                    if (bit_cnt == 3'd7) state_next = STATE_STOP_BIT;\n                    else state_next = STATE_DATA_BITS;\n                end\n\n            STATE_STOP_BIT:\n                begin\n                    if (in == 1'b1) state_next = STATE_IDLE;\n                    else state_next = STATE_ERROR_WAIT;\n                end\n\n            STATE_ERROR_WAIT:\n                begin\n                    // Wait until stop bit (1) appears\n                    if (in == 1'b1) state_next = STATE_IDLE;\n                    else state_next = STATE_ERROR_WAIT;\n                end\n\n            default:\n                begin\n                    state_next = STATE_IDLE;\n                end\n        endcase\n    end\n\n    // Output assignments\n    assign out_byte = out_byte_reg;\n    assign done = done_reg;\n\nendmodule"
